passages.text: August 29, 2025 01:24 AM GMT
Caterpillar Inc | North America
We lower our CAT EPS estimates on the back of expanded steel & aluminum and India tariffs. Increased tariffs pose a negative risk for the other OEMs across our coverage.

We lower our 2025 EPS estimate to \(\) 17.13\(\) (now 6\%\(below cons) driven by increased tariff headwinds CAT now sees a 2025 net tariff headwind of\) \ \(1.5 - 1.8B\) (vs. \(\) 1.3 - 1.5B\(prior) CAT expects a 3Q25 net tariff headwind of\) \ \(500 - 600M\) (vs. \(\) 400 - 500M\(prior) Updated steel, aluminum, and country specific tariffs pose a risk for the rest of the OEMs in our coverage (OSK, TEX, DE, CNH, AGCO, and WAB)

What happened? After the market close, CAT released an 8K (HERE) updating its expected net tariff headwind for FY25. Specifically, it now sees its 2025 net tariff headwind to be in the range of \(\) 1.5 - 1.8B\(\) \ \(1.3 - 1.5B\) previously) and its 3Q25 headwind in the range of \(\) 500 - 600M\(\) \ \(400 - 500M\) previously). Accordingly, CAT now expects its 2025 adj. operating profit to be "near the bottom of the target margin range" vs. bottom half of the target margin range prior. Based on the company's revenue outlook, we believe this implies full year margins will now be approaching \(\sim 16\%\) . According to the company, the updated guide largely reflects: 1) the amendment of the section 232 steel and aluminum tariffs announced last week (HERE), which adds 400+ HTUS codes to the list of items for which steel and aluminum content will be tariffed at \(50\%\) . Importantly, the expanded codes now include certain agriculture machinery, construction machinery, and rail locomotives; and 2) the increased tariff of \(50\%\) on India imports.

Impact on our CAT views and estimates: The latest tariff announcements are broad based and will undoubtedly have an impact across our coverage (direct and indirect). However, our concern remains that CAT and the construction equipment group have thus far exhibited little to no ability to pass through tariffs. As such, the combination of incremental tariff headwinds with higher discounting reserves taken by Deere (DE) for its construction business all bode negatively for CAT's ability to mitigate the incremental risk. As a result of the increased tariff impact, we now lower our 2025 adj. operating profit margins by \(\sim 40\) bps to \(16.3\%\) and adj. EPS by - \(2\%\) to \(\) 17.13\(, putting us even further below consensus for the year. See Exhibit 1 below for a summary of our estimate changes.

tariffs will have negative implications for OEMs in our coverage including construction (CAT, OSK, TEX), agriculture (DE, CNH, AGCO), and Rail & Locomotive OEMs (WAB). Worth noting that commercial vehicle OEMs in our coverage (PCAR, CMI) at this point appear to be exempt as commercial vehicles for the transport of goods have been excluded from the expanded steel and aluminum tariffs. That said, over the medium term they are not necessarily immune as the administration continues its 232 Heavy Truck specific investigation (HERE). We expect pricing power to be the biggest determinant of companies' ability to mitigate the elevated risk, which makes us relatively less concerned about WAB and CMI vs. the rest of the OEM cohort.

We see an increasingly negative set up for shares of CAT into 2H25 and 2026. Rising evidence of an oversupplied construction equipment market combined with our more cautious views on US Non- Resi construction, we think will pressure CI segment earnings. Moreover, we see limited offset to this headwind from manufacturing costs or E&T segment strength, pointing to risk of negative earnings revisions. With the stock at all time highs and the multiple discounting an earnings trough on what we think can be argued, we see a negative risk reward skew.

Volume growth turns positive on the back of better than expected re- acceleration in US Construction activity, Mining, and O&G demand. Stronger than expected demand helps offset tariff headwinds. Shares trade up to \(\sim 25x\) NTM P/E, above the high- end of its historical range of 13x to 22.5x and reflecting improved sentiment toward demand and a refocus to secular growth drivers such as data centers and autonomous machinery.

Volume declines - L/MSD% in CI and RI and +LSD% in E&T, on pressured US non- resi, challenged mining and stronger power gen offset by weaker O&G, industrial and transportation. ME&T Op. Inc. margin contracts - 460bps YoY in 25. As a result, the market values shares using an above mid- cycle multiple, or below where shares are currently trading, reflecting downside risk and an uncertain macro backdrop.

Equipment demand decelerates in CI and RI segments as US Mega Projects disappoint and infrastructure spend takes longer than expected. Used equipment inventories rise and prices fall putting pressure on new equipment pricing. Decrements drive operating income \(\sim 40\%\) lower in 2025 yoy. Valuation multiple rises to \(\sim 22.5x\) NTM P/E, the top end of the company's historical range of 13x to 22.5x reflecting trough earnings.
